US productivity rises 2.7 percent in the first quarter 
US productivity rose an annualized 2.7 percent in the first three
months of the year, the Labor Department said Wednesday.
Productivity growth in the non-farm workplace during the first quarter
was much stronger than the 0.7 percent reported in the department's
previous estimate.
Analysts had forecast an improvement ranging between 0.7 percent and
1.3 percent.
Productivity -- output per number of hours worked -- grew in the 1994
fourth quarter a revised 4.3 percent, up from an initial estimate of
four percent.
